A(x)=\int_{-2}^{x} f(t)\ \mathrm{d}t
f(t)=-1
t<0
f(t)=1
t \geq 0
\epsilon
\delta
\lim_{x \rightarrow 0} A(x)
L
\epsilon>0
\delta>0
\left|A(x)-L\right|<\epsilon
0<\vert x\vert<\delta
L=-2
\delta=\epsilon
x=\frac{1}{2}\epsilon<\delta
\lim_{x \rightarrow 0} A(x)=L=-2
\left|A(x)-L\right|=\left|\int_{-2}^{\frac{1}{2}\epsilon} f(t)\ \mathrm{d}t+2\right|=\left|\int_{-2}^{0} -1\ \mathrm{d}t+\int_{0}^{\frac{1}{2}\epsilon} 1\ \mathrm{d}t+2\right| = \left|\frac{1}{2}\epsilon\right|=\frac{1}{2}\epsilon<\epsilon
x=\frac12\epsilon
\forall x\in \mathbb{R}^*
x=\frac12\epsilon
x\to 0^-
A(0)=-2
x>0
x<0
\epsilon>0
\delta=\epsilon
A(x)=\int_{-2}^0f(t)\, dt+\int_0^xf(t)\, dt=\int_{-2}^0-1\, dt+\int_0^xf(t)\, dt=-2+\int_0^xf(t)\, dt
A(x)=-2+\int_0^xf(t)\, dt=-2+\int_0^x1\, dt=-2+\left|x\right|
A(x)=-2+\int_0^xf(t)\, dt=-2+\int_0^x-1\, dt=-2-x=-2+\left|x\right|
\left|x\right|<\delta\implies \left|A(x)-A(0)\right|=\left|-2+\left|x\right|+2\right|=\left|x\right|<\delta=\epsilon
